@maht0rz In the docs it states that you can use `.value` to return the value from a proof verification, like so:

```
@method myMethod(someProof: SomeProgram.Proof) {
    proof.verify();
    const valid: Bool = proof.value;

    // other code here
}
```

Reference: https://docs.minaprotocol.com/zkapps/o1js/recursion

However, it appears that your goal is be able to generate a proof even if the proof provided as a private input is invalid. I may have a solution for your case, based on my reading of the documentation, code examples, and the source OCaml code. Please note, that it may be incorrect, and @gregor could attest to its validity.

What if you simply wrap `proof.verify()` in a try/catch, making it look something like the following:

```
@method myMethod(innerProof: SomeProgram.Proof) {
    let isValid: Bool = false;

    try {
      innerProof.verify();
      isValid = true;
    } catch (e) {
      // inner proof failed verification
    }

    // isValid will be false if inner proof verification failed
    const valid = Bool(isValid); 

    // ... more code here 
```

It appears that `verify()`in O1JS calls the underlying `verify()` function defined in `groth16.ml` and throws an exception if it fails. I will leave links to all of the references below. Please note, this is just my understanding after a quick examination into the problem, I'm sure @gregor will be able to quickly validate or invalidate my understanding.

Referrences:

* `groth16.ml`: https://github.com/o1-labs/snarky/blob/fa2cb9be5f61b93d5892bd7c838a0ff230d8dd7f/snarkette/groth16.ml#L88
* Mina Reference: https://docs.minaprotocol.com/zkapps/o1js-reference/modules

@maht0rz I have another answer for you:

1. Pass the proof as a private input to your method
2. Get the verification key
3. Convert the proof to JSON
4. Verify the proof directly with `verify`

You can do it like this:

```
import { verify } from 'o1js';

const ok = await verify(proof.toJSON(), verificationKey);
```
